alist strain of antislavery. Engaging the works of Douglass, Thoreau, and Whitman, and Dickinson, Cristin Ellis identifies and traces the emergence of an antislavery materialism in mid-nineteenth century American literature, placing race at the center of the history of posthumanist thought. Turning to contemporary debates now unfolding between posthumanist and critical race theorists, Ellis demonstrates how this antebellum posthumanism highlights the difficulty of reconciling materialist ontologies of the human with the project of social justice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aAntislavery movementszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aHumanismy19th century. 0aSocial justice. 4aAmerican Studies. 4aEnvironment. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aHISTORY / United States / Civil War Period (1850-1877).2bisacsh  aAntislavery.  aBiopolitics.  aFrederick Douglass.  aHenry David Thoreau.  aNew Materialism.  aNonhuman.  aPosthumanism.  aRacial Science.  aSlavery.  aWalt Whitman.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z97831107290090 cprintz978082327844240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823278473?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823278473zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823278473/original  a978-3-11-072900-9 Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA